tool.name: Nicher_SDM

param.name: in_topo_tifs
param.displayname: Input topographic variables and variable type
param.dialogReference:
One or more GeoTIFF raster files representing various topographic variables associated with the target species. For each topographic variable, variable type must be set. If classified data is used, set to Categorical, else use Continuous.

Some example of topographic variables include: slope, aspect, valley depth, solar radiaton, topographic wetness index.

Note: input GeoTIFF rasters must all be of the same spatial extent, have one band per GeoTIFF raster, and all be in the coordinate system GDA94 Australian Albers (EPSG 3577).

param.name: out_sdm_nc_path
param.dialogReference: The folder location and filename of the output NetCDF file containing SDM map data.

param.name: in_occurrence_feat
param.dialogReference:
A feature layer or shapefile of species presence points representing known GDV species locations (occurrences). It is recommended that all point should represent one (or very similar) potential GDV species.

Occurrences points are used to perform machine learning to derive potential landscape habitat or "niche" based on unique combinations of input topographic variable pixels.

Note: the feature of shapefile must be projected in GDA 94 Australian Albers (EPSG: 3577).

param.name: in_num_pseudos
param.dialogReference: The number of psuedo-absence points to generate for the model. Pseudo-absence points are key in SDM work. As a general rule of thumb, use at least the same number of presence points present in the input shapefile.

param.name: in_exclusion_buffer
param.dialogReference: The exclusion buffer (in metres) that will be generated around existing presence points. This is to ensure pseudo-absence points are not generated on top of presence locations - an issue that can confuse the machine learning algorithm.

param.name: in_equalise_absence
param.dialogReference: Whether or not to reduce the number of pseudo-absence points to match the number of presence points once occurrence data has been cleaned and prepared.

param.name: in_etimator
param.dialogReference:
The SDM machine learning algorithm. Options include: decision tree classifiers

- Random Forest: a random forest is a meta estimator that fits a number of classifying decision trees on various sub-samples of the dataset and uses averaging to improve the predictive accuracy and control over-fitting (Breiman, L. 2001).

- Extra Trees: a meta estimator that fits a number of randomized decision trees (a.k.a. extra-trees) on various sub-samples of the dataset and uses averaging to improve the predictive accuracy and control over-fitting.

param.name: in_num_estimators
param.dialogReference: The number of estimators (or trees) in the Random Forest or Extra Trees algorithms.

param.name: in_num_replicates
param.dialogReference: The number of model replications performed. If more than one is set, the average of the model outputs is produced in the output NetCDF.

param.name: in_test_ratio
param.dialogReference:
The percentage of presence and pseudo-absence points to "put aside" for testing model performance after training. Between 10% and 25% recommended.

Note: input value range between 0 to 1, 0.1 being 10%.

param.name: in_add_result_to_map
param.dialogReference: Whether to visualise the results to the currently active map once modelling is complete or not.

tool.summary:
Nicher predicts the distribution of a plant species potential habitat across geographic time and space using machine learning, individual plant presence point locations, and digital elevation model-derived topographic variables (e.g. slope, topographic wetness index, aspect, raw elevation). This process is typically known as Species Distribution Modelling (SDM) or Ecological Niche Modelling (ENM). SDM and ENM typically uses presence points only and generates random pseudo-absences for modelling.

Note: this method does not generate topographic variables, these must be pre-generated prior. The GIS software SAGA makes generation of topographic variables from a digital elevation model (DEM) easy and is recommended.

See citation: Booth, T.H., Nix, H.A., Busby, J.R. and Hutchinson, M.F., 2014. BIOCLIM: the first species distribution modelling package, its early applications and relevance to most current MAXENT studies. Diversity and Distributions, 20(1), pp.1-9.
